Gibbs Sampler Example

Here, are goal is to simulate bivariate draws of (\(\theta_1, \theta_2\)) from the multivariate normal distribution, where:

\[\begin{pmatrix} \theta_1 \\ \theta_2 \end{pmatrix} \mid y \sim N\left(\begin{pmatrix}y_1 \\ y_2 \end{pmatrix}, \begin{pmatrix} 1 & \rho \\ \rho & 1\end{pmatrix} \right)\] We will use a Gibbs sampler to do this and compare with directly drawing from this distribution as an example.

The Gibbs sampler proceeds in two alternating steps. First, take a random first guess \(\theta^0\). Then, for \(t > 0\)

  1. Simulate \(\theta_1^t \sim N(y_1 + \rho(\theta_2 - y_2), 1 - \rho^2)\)
  2. Simulate \(\theta_2^t \sim N(y_2 + \rho(\theta_1 - y_1), 1 - \rho^2)\)

For the sake of an example, set \((y_1, y_2) = (1, 1)\) and set \(\rho = 0.8\) We implement this Gibbs Sampler below.

gibbs.normal <- function(y1, y2, rho, theta0, N, burnin){
  #y1 and y2 - observed data 
  #rho - the correlation between theta1 and theta2
  #theta0 - initial guess (two dimensional vector)
  #N - total number of simulations
  #burnin - how many of the initial simulations should be tossed?
  theta1 <- rep(0, N+burnin) 
  theta2 <- rep(0, N+burnin)
  theta1[1] <- theta0[1]
  theta2[1] <- theta0[2]
  for(s in 2:(N+burnin)){
    theta1[s] <- rnorm(1, mean = y1 + rho*(theta2[s-1] - y2), 
                       sd = sqrt(1 - rho^2))
    theta2[s] <- rnorm(1, mean = y2 + rho*(theta1[s] - y1), 
                       sd = sqrt(1 - rho^2))
  }
  result <- data.frame(theta1 = theta1[(burnin+1):(N+burnin)], 
                       theta2 = theta2[(burnin+1):(N+burnin)])
  return(result)
}

Sample with no burnin and 1000 simulations

set.seed(123)
samples <- gibbs.normal(y1 = 1, y2 = 1, rho = 0.8, theta0 = c(1, 5), N = 10000, burnin = 0)

Plot the samples values of \(\theta_1\) and \(\theta_2\) to inspect convergence

     main = expression(theta[1]))

Metropolis Algorithm Example

Continuing with the above example, we now try the Metropolis algorithm using the proposal distribution \(N(\theta^{t-1}, I)\) for the observed possible simulation \(\theta^*\).

metropolis.normal <- function(y1, y2, rho, theta0, N, burnin){
  #theta0 - an initial guess (must be 2-dimensional vector)
  #N - number of simulations
  #burnin - number of burnin samples
  theta1 <- rep(0, N+burnin) 
  theta2 <- rep(0, N+burnin)
  theta1[1] <- theta0[1]
  theta2[1] <- theta0[2]
  Sigma <- cbind(c(1, rho), c(rho, 1))
  #function to calculate the ratio using unnormalized part of the density function for a Normal(y, Sigma)
  ratio <- function(theta.new, theta.old){
    numerator <- exp(-.5*t(theta.new - c(y1, y2))%*%solve(Sigma)%*%(theta.new - c(y1, y2)))
    denominator <- exp(-.5*t(theta.old - c(y1, y2))%*%solve(Sigma)%*%(theta.old - c(y1, y2)))
    r <- numerator / denominator
    return(min(r,1))
  }
  
  for(s in 2:(N + burnin)){
    theta.new <- mvrnorm(n = 1, mu = c(theta1[s-1], theta2[s-1]), Sigma = diag(2))
    theta.old <- c(theta1[s-1], theta2[s-1])
    r <- ratio(theta.new, theta.old)
    U <- runif(1, 0, 1)
    if(U < r){
      theta1[s] <- theta.new[1]
      theta2[s] <- theta.new[2]
    }
    if(U >= r){
      theta1[s] <- theta1[s-1]
      theta2[s] <- theta2[s-1]
    }
  }
  result <- data.frame(theta1 = theta1[(burnin+1):(N+burnin)], 
                       theta2 = theta2[(burnin+1):(N+burnin)])
  return(result)
}

Run Metropolis

sample.Metropolis <- metropolis.normal(y1 = 1, y2 = 1, rho = 0.8,
                                       theta0 = c(1,1), N = 10000,
                                       burnin = 0)

Plot diagnostics and plot these results against the truth

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot(y = sample.Metropolis$theta1, x = 1:10000, xlab = "Sample", ylab = "Value", type = "l", col = "blue",
     main = expression(theta[1]))
plot(y = sample.Metropolis$theta2, x = 1:10000, xlab = "Sample", ylab = "Value", type = "l", col = "red",
     main = expression(theta[2]))

Again, it looks fairly stationary past perhaps a burnin of 1000. Let’s look at those values against the truth.

     xlab = expression(theta[1]), ylab = expression(theta[2]), 
     main = "Metropolis Samples")

     ylab = expression(theta[2]), main = "Direct Samples")

Metropolis-Hastings Algorithm Example

Continuing with the above example, we now try the Metropolis-Hastings algorithm using the proposal distribution \(N((0.8\theta^{t-1}, I)\) for the observed possible simulation \(\theta^*\).

Important point here: we really only need to change our ratio function from the metropolis.normal function above. We do that in the next code.

Note: Try different multipliers of \(\theta^{t-1}\) to see major differences in how long it takes M-H to converge.

metropolis.hastings.normal <- function(y1, y2, rho, theta0, N, 
                                       burnin){
  #theta0 - an initial guess (must be 2-dimensional vector)
  #N - number of simulations
  #burnin - number of burnin samples
  theta1 <- rep(0, N+burnin) 
  theta2 <- rep(0, N+burnin)
  theta1[1] <- theta0[1]
  theta2[1] <- theta0[2]
  Sigma <- cbind(c(1, rho), c(rho, 1))
  #function to calculate the ratio using unnormalized part of the density function for a Normal(y, Sigma)
  ratio <- function(theta.new, theta.old){
    numerator1 <- exp(-.5*t(theta.new - c(y1, y2))%*%solve(Sigma)%*%(theta.new - c(y1, y2)))
    
    #J(theta.old | theta.new)
    numerator2 <- dnorm(theta.old[1], mean = .8*theta.new[1], sd = 1) * 
      dnorm(theta.old[2], mean = .8*theta.new[2], sd = 1)
    
    denominator1 <- exp(-.5*t(theta.old - c(y1, y2))%*%solve(Sigma)%*%(theta.old - c(y1, y2)))
    #J(theta.new | theta.old)
    denominator2 <- dnorm(theta.new[1], mean = .8*theta.old[1], sd = 1) * 
      dnorm(theta.new[2], mean = .8*theta.old[2], sd = 1)
    
    r <- (numerator1*numerator2) / (denominator1*denominator2)
    return(min(r,1))
  }
  
  for(s in 2:(N + burnin)){
    theta.new <- mvrnorm(n = 1, mu = .8*c(theta1[s-1], theta2[s-1]), Sigma = diag(2))
    theta.old <- c(theta1[s-1], theta2[s-1])
    r <- ratio(theta.new, theta.old)
    U <- runif(1, 0, 1)
    if(U < r){
      theta1[s] <- theta.new[1]
      theta2[s] <- theta.new[2]
    }
    if(U >= r){
      theta1[s] <- theta1[s-1]
      theta2[s] <- theta2[s-1]
    }
  }
  result <- data.frame(theta1 = theta1[(burnin+1):(N+burnin)], 
                       theta2 = theta2[(burnin+1):(N+burnin)])
  return(result)
}

Run Metropolis-Hastings

sample.Metropolis.Hastings <- metropolis.hastings.normal(y1 = 1, 
                                       y2 = 1, rho = 0.8,
                                       theta0 = c(1,1), N = 10000,
                                       burnin = 0)

Plot Diagnostics and Compare against true distribution

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot(y = sample.Metropolis.Hastings$theta1, x = 1:10000, xlab = "Sample", ylab = "Value", type = "l", col = "blue",
     main = expression(theta[1]))
plot(y = sample.Metropolis.Hastings$theta2, x = 1:10000, xlab = "Sample", ylab = "Value", type = "l", col = "red",
     main = expression(theta[2]))

Again, it looks fairly stationary past perhaps a burnin of 1000. Let’s look at those values against the truth.

     xlab = expression(theta[1]), ylab = expression(theta[2]), 
     main = "Metropolis-Hastings Samples")
plot(y = true.values[, 1], x = true.values[, 2], xlab = expression(theta[1]), 
     ylab = expression(theta[2]), main = "Direct Samples")
